    "solution": "<p>Given that $\\alpha = \\sin 36^\\circ$, we need to determine which equation it is a root of.</p>\n\n<p>We start with the known relationship for $\\cos 72^\\circ$:</p>\n\n<p>$ \\cos 72^\\circ = \\frac{\\sqrt{5}-1}{4} $</p>\n\n<p>Using the double-angle formula for cosine:</p>\n\n<p>$ \\cos 72^\\circ = 1 - 2 \\sin^2 36^\\circ $</p>\n\n<p>Substitute $\\alpha$ for $\\sin 36^\\circ$:</p>\n\n<p>$ 1 - 2\\alpha^2 = \\frac{\\sqrt{5}-1}{4} $</p>\n\n<p>Multiply both sides by 4:</p>\n\n<p>$ 4 - 8\\alpha^2 = \\sqrt{5} - 1 $</p>\n\n<p>Add 1 to both sides:</p>\n\n<p>$ 5 - 8\\alpha^2 = \\sqrt{5} $</p>\n\n<p>Square both sides to eliminate the radical:</p>\n\n<p>$ (5 - 8\\alpha^2)^2 = 5 $</p>\n\n<p>Expand the left side:</p>\n\n<p>$ 25 + 64\\alpha^4 - 80\\alpha^2 = 5 $</p>\n\n<p>Simplify by subtracting 5 from both sides:</p>\n\n<p>$ 64\\alpha^4 - 80\\alpha^2 + 20 = 0 $</p>\n\n<p>Divide the entire equation by 4:</p>\n\n<p>$ 16\\alpha^4 - 20\\alpha^2 + 5 = 0 $</p>\n\n<p>Thus, the equation $16\\alpha^4 - 20\\alpha^2 + 5 = 0$ is the one for which $\\alpha = \\sin 36^\\circ$ is a root.</p>",
